[1] Australia (VIC)
Date: Wed 2 Mar 2011
From: Lucinda Franklin <lucinda.franklin@health.vic.gov.au>


Re: Recent measles outbreak in Victoria
---------------------------------------
The Communicable Disease Prevention and Control Unit of the Victorian
Government Department of Health is continuing to investigate the
recent increase in imported cases of measles to Victoria [See: Measles
- Australia (Victoria) 20010216.0309]. As of Tue 1 Mar 2011, a total
of 16 confirmed cases had been notified to the department. There were
3 cases aged less than 12 months, 3 aged between 5 and 16 years, 6
aged from 20 to 37 years, and the remainder were aged 45 to 66 years.
13 cases were reported to be not vaccinated and 3 cases were of
unknown vaccination status.

Epidemiological investigations undertaken by the department and
genotyping by the Victorian Infectious Diseases Reference Laboratory
established the presence of at least 4 distinct genotype clusters. An
additional 5 cases are awaiting genotyping, of which 3 are suspected
to have been acquired overseas and 2 in Victoria, although no
epidemiological link between these 2 latter cases and other cases has
been established to date. The index case in each of the 4 distinct
genotype clusters (which includes 2 clusters of genotype D4, genotype
D8 and genotype D9) acquired their infection overseas (South Asia,
South East Asia, and the UK). Only one of the index cases so far has
resulted in further cases at this stage. This particular cluster has
seen 2nd and 3rd generations of cases. Situations in which
transmission has occurred include household contacts, health
facilities, and a supermarket. Most notable in this cluster are the 2
cases aged 60 and 66 years (who are siblings). These cases fall
outside of the defined 'population at risk' for measles (i.e., those
born during or after 1966 when the vaccination became available in
Australia). These 2 cases were found to have spent their childhood in
a relatively remote rural region of Victoria, and presumably had never
been exposed to the measles virus before now.

6 of the 9 "index cases" (including those not linked to further
cases) have been identified as unvaccinated (vaccination status for
the remaining 3 cases was unknown). High immunisation coverage in
Victoria -- 93 per cent for one dose by 2 years of age, and 91 per
cent for 2 doses by 5 years of age appears to have assisted in halting
further transmission from the other index cases.

The department has undertaken a number of measures to control the
spread of disease including follow up of contacts (who are then
recommended for measles vaccine or normal human immunoglobulin, where
indicated) and health alerts to general practitioners, hospital
emergency departments. The department issued a health alert to the
general public via the media on 17 Feb 2011 to remind travellers to
check their vaccination status before travelling.

--
Lucinda Franklin
Epidemiologist - Epidemiology and Surveillance
Communicable Disease Prevention and Control
Health Protection Branch
Department of Health
Level 14 50 Lonsdale Street
Melbourne
Victoria 3000
Australia
<lucinda.franklin@health.vic.gov.au>

[This report demonstrates the power of genotyping in the elucidating
the features of epidemics involving imported cases, something that
could be adopted by others with profit. - Mod.CP]

