[3] USA (WA)
Date: Wed 2 Mar 2011
Source: oregonlive.com [abbreviated & edited]
<http://www.oregonlive.com/clark-county/index.ssf/2011/03/clark_county_investigates_second_child_measles_case_in_a_month.html>


Clark County investigates second child measles case in a month
--------------------------------------------------------------
A 2nd case of measles within a month in Clark County, this one in a
school-age child, is under investigation by health officials [for
information on first child see: 'Measles - USA (02): (WA) alert
20110216.0512']. The child was exposed 2 weeks ago at a medical
facility visited by the 1st stricken child, a 7 month old returned
with his family from a trip to India, said Dr Alan Melnick, the county
health officer. The baby developed the telltale red measles rash while
flying for more than 20 hours to Portland International Airport on 13
Feb 2011. He may have been coughing and sneezing -- the primary way
the highly contagious disease is transmitted. The next day, the baby
was taken to 2 medical facilities in Vancouver: the Evergreen
Pediatric Clinic and the pharmacy or outpatient lab at the Southwest
Washington Medical Center, officials said.

The school-age child had not been vaccinated when exposed, Melnick
said. That child visited the 7-Eleven store at 5101 NE 112th Ave in
Vancouver between 4 and 8 pm on Sun 27 Feb 2011, while contagious.

Health officials urged people who might have been exposed and have
not been vaccinated to avoid going out in public for 7 to 21 days
following exposure. In this case, the period starts Sun 6 Mar 2011 and
runs to Sun 20 Mar 2011. They also should seek vaccinations, although
the vaccine is most effective within just 3 days of exposure. Pregnant
women or people with immune system issues can receive immune globulin
shots within 6 days of exposure, in this case, by 8 pm on Sat 5 Mar
2011.

