[4] USA - multistate alert, clarification
Date: Thu 3 Mar 2011
From: Paul Ettestad <Paul.Ettestad@state.nm.us>


re: "Measles Outbreak: Tens of Thousands Exposed?"
Part (1) of Measles Update 2011 (02) 20110301.0677
--------------------------------------------------
In order to avoid confusion, here is the flight itinerary of the
measles case in a New Mexico resident, most likely exposed to measles
while visiting in London. No secondary cases have been identified in
New Mexico to date.

Case departed London-Heathrow at around noon on 20 Feb 2011 on United
flight 0919, arriving at Washington Dulles on the afternoon of Sun 20
Feb 2011. The case then spent 2 days in Washington DC before departing
on Southwest flight 3423 from Baltimore-Washington International
Airport on a 6:50pm scheduled flight to Denver on 22 Feb 2011, where
the case exited the plane at around 9 pm. Flight 3423 continued on to
San Diego without the case, but most likely had passengers on board
who were potentially exposed. The case then took Southwest flight 2605
from Denver to Albuquerque. Flight 2605 left Denver around 10pm on 22
Feb 2011 and arrived in Albuquerque a little before midnight on 22 Feb
2011.

Case had illness onset on 18 Feb 2011 and rash onset on 20 Feb 2011,
so was contagious on all of these flights.

Public health officials from jurisdictions with passengers on these
flights are following up to check immune status, offer measles vaccine
or immunoglobulin, and conducting surveillance for possible secondary
cases.

--
Paul Ettestad DVM, MS
State Public Health Veterinarian
New Mexico Department of Health
<Paul.Ettestad@state.nm.us>

[ProMED-mail thanks Paul Ettestad for providing this lucid
clarification of the itinerary of the measles-infected passenger en
route from London (UK) to Albuquerque (NM). As of Mon 7 Mar 2011 there
have been no secondary cases reported along the patient's route or at
her final destination. The incubation period for measles virus
infection is 10-12 days, with the characteristic rash appearing by 14
days after exposure. - Mod.CP]

